From: Claude (devcontainer agent)
Date: 2026-04-26
Subject: [I1, I2, I4, I6, S4] .devcontainer/post_install.py:
         stop silently destroying user customizations + opt-in bypass +
         drop host-gitconfig include

Why this is a separate patch
============================
This devcontainer mounts /workspace/.devcontainer as read-only inside the
container, so an agent running inside cannot edit post_install.py
directly. Apply this patch from the host (or any environment with write
access to .devcontainer/), then commit and push.

The C1 patch in this directory (`C1-post_install-onboarding-bypass.patch`)
covers ~/.claude.json. This patch covers the four sibling functions in
the same file plus a security-hardening change to the bypassPermissions
default and an exception-handling broadening in fix_directory_ownership.

What this fixes
===============

I1 — `setup_claude_settings` silently destroys customized settings on
JSONDecodeError
--------------------------------------------------------------------
The function uses `with contextlib.suppress(json.JSONDecodeError):` —
on parse failure, settings stays {}, then is rewritten with only
`permissions.defaultMode = "bypassPermissions"`. Any user-authored
~/.claude/settings.json (custom hooks, allow-list, env, model
preferences) is silently destroyed on every container rebuild.

The patch mirrors C1's discipline: on JSONDecodeError, shutil.move the
existing file to settings.json.bak, log a stderr warning, then proceed
with {}. The user can inspect the .bak and recover manually.

I2 — `setup_global_gitignore` overwrites user-customized files
unconditionally
--------------------------------------------------------------------
`gitignore.write_text(...)` and `local_gitconfig.write_text(...)` ran
unconditionally on every postCreateCommand invocation. The sibling
`setup_tmux_config` uses an `if file.exists(): return` guard; these two
did not. User customizations to ~/.gitignore_global (added language
patterns) or ~/.gitconfig.local (custom [delta], [merge] overrides,
signing config) were destroyed on every container rebuild.

The patch adds the same existence guard to both writes — independently,
since one may exist while the other does not.

I4 — `bypassPermissions` enabled unconditionally
--------------------------------------------------------------------
`setup_claude_settings` writes `permissions.defaultMode =
"bypassPermissions"` regardless of whether the developer has opted in.
Combined with the `claude-yolo` alias, NET_ADMIN/NET_RAW caps, and an
R/W workspace mount, every "Reopen in Container" makes Claude
permission-free by default with no signal to the developer.

The patch gates the bypass write behind a `SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_BYPASS`
env var: explicitly opt-in, default off. The `claude-yolo` alias in
.zshrc continues to work without the env var (it passes
--dangerously-skip-permissions explicitly).

This is a behavior change for existing dev workflows that relied on
bypass-by-default; restore by setting `SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_BYPASS=1`
in devcontainer.json's `remoteEnv` or via `localEnv` pass-through.
Document the variable in CONTRIBUTING.md (separate commit, not part
of this patch).

I6 — Host gitconfig included into container — directives execute
under bypassPermissions
--------------------------------------------------------------------
`setup_global_gitignore` wrote `~/.gitconfig.local` containing
`[include] path = {host_gitconfig}`. Git resolves directives in the
included file when running git commands inside the container, including
core.pager, core.fsmonitor, core.editor, [alias] xyz = !shell-cmd,
[diff "lfs"] command = …. Anything in the developer's host gitconfig
executed inside the container, where Claude runs with bypassPermissions.

The patch drops the `[include]` directive and instead reads specific
safe keys (user.name, user.email, user.signingkey, commit.gpgsign)
from the host gitconfig via `git config --file {host_gitconfig} --get`,
writing them as literal values into the local config. Result:
  - Identity propagates (commits attributed to the host user)
  - No alias / pager / editor / fsmonitor / lfs hook can leak through
  - Side-effect: any non-listed host config (custom merge tools, diff
    drivers, hook frameworks) does NOT propagate. Set
    SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_INCLUDE_HOST_GITCONFIG=1 to opt back into the
    [include] form, with the security caveat documented in the comment.

S4 — `fix_directory_ownership` exception list is too narrow
--------------------------------------------------------------------
`except (PermissionError, subprocess.CalledProcessError)` did not catch
bare OSError (FileNotFoundError from a stale symlink, NotADirectoryError
mid-mount race). An uncaught exception propagated and skipped the
remaining `setup_global_gitignore()` call, leaving the dev environment
half-configured. Captured chown stderr was also never surfaced — only
the exception's repr was printed.

The patch broadens to `except (OSError, subprocess.CalledProcessError)`
and prints the captured stderr from CalledProcessError so the chown
failure is debuggable.

How to apply
============
From a shell on the host (NOT inside the devcontainer):

  cd <smudge repo root>
  git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/I1-I2-I4-I6-S4-post_install-hardening.patch
  git add .devcontainer/post_install.py
  git commit -m "fix(devcontainer): preserve user customizations + opt-in bypass + drop host gitconfig include (I1, I2, I4, I6, S4)"

Then update CONTRIBUTING.md to document SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_BYPASS and
SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_INCLUDE_HOST_GITCONFIG (separate commit; not part
of this patch).

